You&rsquo;re a military demolitions expert working in hostile territory that&rsquo;s been called in to defuse a massive car bomb found outside a luxury resort hotel.  You&rsquo;ve evacuated the parking lot and setup your equipment; you begin to examine the bomb when suddenly the bomb timer starts to countdown from 16 minutes and your heart rate just went into overdrive.  Upon further inspection you notice the bomb is controlled by an encrypted code sequencer and you need to figure out how to connect your Code Analyzer to the bomb&rsquo;s timer.  Your new high-tech Code Analyzer is used to bypass the bomb&rsquo;s timer and prevent the bomb from exploding. To do this you must figure out the wiring sequence from the mass of wires in front of you and rewiring the device to include your code analyzer, which will override the timer and allow you to defuse the bomb safely!  You have less than 16 minutes to figure out the wiring sequence and connect your Code Analyzer.  If you can figure out this circuit and connect each of the four individual wires from the bomb timer to your code analyzer, you will safely stop the timer and eventually defuse the bomb; saving the resort from certain disaster!  Countdown to disaster begins&hellip;

Countdown to Disaster is a combination tile placement, card management game and race against the clock style game. Your Code Analyzer has [4] color coded wires &ldquo;Red, Green, Blue and Yellow&rdquo; which must be connected to the timer of the bomb so as to be able to bypass the timer and prevent the bomb from exploding! These connections will be made through the [16] wire routing tiles on the game board. The bomb itself is amass of wires, which is represented by the 4x4 grid of wire tiles on the game board that are routed in different directions to try and prevent you from defusing the robot. Your goal is to figure out the four individual wire routes to connect your code analyzer to the robot's timer. You must figure out a complete connection route for each wire from the code analyzer to the bomb's timer before the timer runs out and the bomb explodes!
You have special wiring tools that allow you to manipulate the wires and create or change the route of each existing wire or wires. With your tools in hand you can swap wires vertically and horizontally 1, 2, or 3 spaces. You can also rotate the direction of a specific wire or wire group up to 360 degrees. The last tool allows you to actually cut out &ldquo;replace&rdquo; a wire or wire group with a new wire or wire group from the bottom four tiles! When you replace a wire or wire group you can rotate the tile to the position of your choice.

Deep in the bowels of the fetid swamps and shadowed woods of Louisiana, evil lurks. Dark Priests of hidden religions make blood sacrifices in the name of the All Mother, The Black Goat of the Woods, the mighty and terrible Shub-Niggurath. Soon this darkness will cover all of the city of New Orleans, for her thousand young are spreading and ready for flesh&hellip;

The Thousand Young is the ninth deluxe expansion for Call of Cthulhu: The Card Game. Its 165 cards (three copies each of 55 different cards) add new depth and resilience to the Shub-Niggurath faction. Nearly two-thirds of the expansion&rsquo;s cards bolster the All Mother&rsquo;s ranks with Ghouls, Dark Young, Monsters, Mi-Go, and Cultists. You&rsquo;ll also find ghastly new Locations, foul Curses, and a new version of the Villainous Dark Mother, herself.

Still, the Black Goat of the Woods is not the region&rsquo;s only corrupting influence. In the heart of the Big Easy, Nyarlathotep&rsquo;s many Avatars play a deep and complicated game, manipulating human agencies and monstrous cultists, alike. These Avatars infiltrate every one of the game&rsquo;s eight factions, even as the factions all gain mysterious new Locations that afford players new interactions with the top cards of their decks.

The Anarchy  is the name given to the civil war over the succession to the throne of Henry I Beauclerc, King of England and Duke of Normandy, from 1135 to 1154. This war opposed Stephen of Blois and the Empress Matilda, wife of Geoffrey Plantagenet. Numerous castle sieges took place during this period, so this was the perfect opportunity to update all the siege rules of the various games of the Game: Cry Havoc System. The tactical game includes various siege engines including a new, bigger battering ram that is more realistic than the one that was included with Siege.

THE ANARCHY is an extension to Guiscard and Diex Aïe and needs the rules of one of these two games (available as a free download) to be played.

Box Contents:

> (3) full-color tactical maps, giving a possibility of many different terrains;
> (3) sheets of overlays with siege engines, hoarding and scaffolding;
> (2) sheets of tactical counters printed in full color;
> (1) full-color campaign map ;
> (2) sheets of counters for the campaign game printed in full color;
> (1) 36-page rule booklet;
> (1) 36-page booklet including the historical background, a guide to the playing pieces and both tactical and campaign scenarios;
> (8) play sheets for handy reference;
> (1) 10-sided die;

An optional counter tray is available in the Shoppe of Cry Havoc Fan.

The game is available in 2 versions:
> English (Both booklets and play sheets in English)
> French (Both booklets and play sheets in French)

Travel back to when the arcade was a dark, smoky den of iniquity.&nbsp; Fame and respect can be bought for only a quarter if you have the skill.&nbsp; Once you fill up the high score table on a game then you are the king!&nbsp; Put a quarter on the glass and challenge the champ if you think you've got what it takes!&nbsp;

Anarcade is a deck building game of stack control.  Players play starter cards to earn Coins and buy better cards from the Game stacks. They can also use Coins to Score on the Games.  Each player attempts to fill up a High Score table to take control of that game before an opponent can do the same. Once a player takes control of a stack, other players can't touch it.  The winner is the first player to control 3 games.

The Raster Red set is tuned for fast action and features pixel based, raster screen, retro arcade goodness!  Combine with any other Anarcade set to expand the game to up to 4 players.

For a long time there is a war, and opponents have decided to resolve it not through a big battle but a struggle between their best knights. But chivalry is able to integrate even the most irreconcilable enemies. Many soldiers from both sides united with different relations: friendship, lifesaving, vows of chivalry, and even love.
&nbsp;
In Сердца и Доспехи ("Hearts and Armour") players are divided into two teams. The task of each team - to defeat the opposing team, and killing or wounding more fighters from the opposite side. However, each player draws a relation card of one of the opponents. He can not win if the opponent is killed.

&ldquo;It is both the duty and the tradition of the Royal Navy to engage the enemy wherever there is water to float a ship&rdquo;

A &ldquo;fast play&rdquo; game covering primarily the naval engagements on Lake Tanganyika during the First World War, and also any number of real and hypothetical small craft actions during the period 1910-1920. Written with 1/600 scale models in mind, their inspiration being the models designed by North Head Miniatures of New Zealand.

As well as the tactical rules, a set of mini campaign rules is included. Actions fought using the tactical rules tend to be short and sharp, and so the campaign is easily playable in a few evenings, or as a club project for a day.

Fightin' Fungi is an advanced incarnation of the Song of Blades and Heroes fantasy skirmish rules &mdash; with a side serving of mushrooms. This stand-alone miniatures game features:

     Plenty of special rules including weapon-based and martial arts traits;
     A detailed magic system with 36 spells;
     Hundreds of ready-to-play profiles, with a point system to add your own;
     A dedicated 28mm miniatures line; 
     A unique setting in a valley populated by mushroom creatures.


As with all games in the Song of Blades and Heroes family, it's a miniatures game with individually activated figures.  There is a press your luck element in deciding how many activation dice to roll: the more successes you roll, the more actions you can take with a given figure.  But if you roll 2+ failures, your turn ends and it might leave you with unactivated troops.

Unlike most games in this system, Fightin' Fungi actually has (optional) miniatures made specifically for the game.

After a long journey crossing never-ending wild seas, the colonies reached a wonderful and prosperous island&hellip; The rush of power began quickly after&hellip; And, the battle for conquering the island to prove who was the master of this mysterious island&hellip; Colonies started to expand their own territories by acquiring more lands&hellip; And, to flourish by harvesting resources... However, the resources were limited &hellip; And, industrialization was inevitably ahead&hellip; So, at a glance, the faces of tiny villages have been changed to modern cities&hellip; Colonies rapidly developed new cities, built massive factories, used airplanes to collect the resources, and scratched the sky with their high-rise business centers... The danger of foreigners was always around&hellip; Hence, the incomers funded the costly militaries to protect their people&hellip; War was not always an option&hellip; Thus, they established diplomacy and started trading with their neighbors&hellip; Famine lead to demand for more lands&hellip; So, the settlers were convinced to invade new lands and raise their own flags on them&hellip; And now this is the question: whose flags will remain waving on the horizon?

Raising the Flags is a strategic board game where every player is a leader of a colony. The winner of the game is the one who creates the most prosperous territory. The game occurs on an island containing various lands and cities. Each player begins the adventure by selecting a capital city and raising the main flag on it. Players should expand the territory with the construction of new buildings such as farms, houses, factories, airports and business centers, and by harvesting crude resources including, food, wood, stone and oil. The players also experience negotiation and trading with neighbors, tricking and attacking them&hellip;
The game board is an island which contains four different tiles, including sea, resources, lands and cities. Each player starts the game by selecting a city as the own capital city and raises the main flag in that capital city. Then, it is time to expand the territory, construct the buildings, generate and trade resources with other players based on some pre-determined rules. The players expand their territory and raise the land flags on them. Then, they start to construct new building on the own territories. Simultaneous with construction of every new building, the player must select a building flag and raise it on the top of that constructed building. Selection of a flag is according to the player&rsquo;s own decision, which can be aimed by the logic of probability. When a player rolls two dices, the summation of both dices will make a number. If this number is matched with any flag number on top of any player&rsquo;s building, the owner player will receive the income of that particular building. Therefore, the territory of each player is expanded according to the optimal construction of the buildings and efficient way of raising the flags. During a gameplay, management of resources/money, planning to expand lands and cities, effective negotiation with neighbors, wise decision to attack other players, defending territory, and of course having a bit of  luck will make a player closer to the final victory.

Ho, traveler! If you would wander these lands, you must prepare yourself; pitiless death stalks all those who roam far here. Carry with you strong iron blades, and cover your shoulders with heavy cloaks. Select with care those hale companions whom you can stoutly trust. I pray ye have honed your skills in combat, or perchance taken on the trade of magics. You will find many aged relics on your path: make use of them, if ye will. For there are those who would pursue you, and their steel is sharp, their ilk stalwart, their wits keen. The fragments of that ancient alliance weaken now, and the tenuous peace of this age threatens to expire&hellip;

Third Age: Eternal exists in an exciting universe where beasts, known as the Awakened, inhabit a land that would not be unfamiliar to the player. As a modular card game, one must select a cadre of heroes, outfit them with arms and armor, call upon the aid of companions, and employ skills and actions to face the opposing player in battle.

In Third Age: Eternal, vitality, a card&rsquo;s life force, is also one&rsquo;s main form of currency, and a delicate balance must be stricken to win&mdash;so weigh your defenses against your offenses or you may quickly find yourself overrun. Certain cards or abilities require additional payment in the form of exhaustion, a card&rsquo;s capacity for exertion; but overwork a companion or gear and you will find it will expire. In Third Age: Eternal, one must constantly balance one&rsquo;s own vitality and exhaustion, which ensures a challenging game of tough choices and rich tactics.

Each deck in Third Age: Eternal can play through wildly different strategies. You may be a hero whose skills with the gun are all you need; or strike among an army of companions and ride into battle with your brothers-in-arms. Or maybe you&rsquo;re a mercenary of magic and action, and you will weave great firestorms to devastate even the largest forces. The possibilities are endless, but you must be clever if you wish to be standing after the dust settles&hellip;

Third Age: Eternal is a robust and customizable game that is unmatched in its flexibility of strategy.
